<HEADLINE>
<P>
MOVIES TO TAPE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Kevin Thomas 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The Hairdresser's Husband (Cinemax Thursday at 5:35 a.m.), French director 
Patrice Leconte's cracked 1992 fairy tale, offers a middle-age man (Jean 
Rochefort) fulfilling a fantasy by marrying a shy, lovely hairdresser (Anna 
Galiena).Their "perfect happiness" contains a stinger. 
</P>
<P>
 Pelle the Conqueror (KCET Saturday at 9 p.m.), Billie August's great 1988 
agrarian epic, pits landowners against farm workers in a state of stark and 
immutable inequity. Also a tender father-and-son story, with a superb Max Von 
Sydow and newcomer Pelle Hvenegaard. 
</P>
<P>
 Babette's Feast (KCET Saturday at 11:30 p.m.) is an exquisite, subtle Isak 
Dinesen fable. Stephane Audran stars in the role of her career. 
</P>
