<P>
 WORLD PRESS PHOTO: 1994 supervising editor Kari Lundelin (Thames & Hudson: 
$19.95; 132 pp., paperback original). The World Press Photo Foundation was 
established in 1955 to provide an international forum for news photographers. 
The winners of their annual contest offer a depressing look at the state of the 
world: violence in the former Yugoslavia, Somalia, Russia and Afghanistan; 
floods and drug abuse in the United States; children suffering from diseases 
caused by the Chernobyl disaster. These dramatic photographs also prove that 
still images retain a special power that is very different from television news 
videos. 
</P>
