<TEXT>
<P>
 HOAXES AND SCAMS: A Compendium of Deceptions, Ruses and Swindles by Carl 
Sifakis (Facts on File: $19.95; 308 pp., illustrated). Sifakis grafts two books 
together in this entertaining volume, a history of famous scandals and an 
analysis of everyday cons. The explanations of rigged carnival games and 
three-card monte (the game hucksters play on New York street corners) can help 
readers avoid being bilked. Sifakis' tongue-in-cheek accounts of famous frauds 
-- from the Affair of the Queen's Necklace that helped to bring down the 
Ancient Regime to Teapot Dome and the television game show scandal that 
inspired "Quiz Show" -- are even more amusing. 
</P>
