<BYLINE>
<P>
By Don Snowden 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 WORLD SAXOPHONE QUARTET 
</P>
<P>
 "Moving Right Along" 
</P>
<P>
 Black Saint  
</P>
<P>
 * * * 
</P>
<P>
 The World Saxophone Quartet finessed the departure of chief composer Julius 
Hemphill by recording with African drummers on its last album four years ago. 
With Eric Person now in the lineup (veteran James Spaulding is featured on two 
tracks here), the group returns with more focus on sonorous ensemble harmonies 
and riff-anchored pieces than fierce collective improvisations or the dense 
harmonic intricacy of Hemphill's works.The net gain in accessibility is 
counterbalanced by a relative lack of challenge -- with nearly two decades 
under its belt, the World Saxophone Quartet may no longer be stretching out 
into new musical frontiers. 
</P>
<P>
 New albums are rated on a scale of one star (poor) to four (excellent).  
</P>
<P>
 Don Snowden 
</P>
