<HEADLINE>
<P>
CRITIC'S PICK: 'THE FUGITIVE' 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Kenneth Turan 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Dr. Richard Kimble (Harrison Ford, pictured) never rests, barely even stops to 
catch his breath. And neither does the film that capitalizes on his 
dilemma.This 1993 blockbuster, based on the '60s TV series, is a 
super-adrenaline stemwinder, a crisp and jolting melodrama that screws the 
tension so tight it does everything but squeak. Laced with breakneck chases and 
eye-widening stunts, "The Fugitive" succeeds because of its other qualities: 
intelligence and wit. Director Andrew Davis, working from a sharp script by Jeb 
Stuart and David Twohy, has paid attention to all the film's characters, 
involving us all the more completely in the action. Tommy Lee Jones turns in an 
Oscar-winning performance as a fearsomely implacable and darkly humorous U.S. 
marshal (HBO Saturday at 8:45 p.m.). Kenneth Turan 
</P>
</TEXT>
