<HEADLINE>
<P>
YOUR MORTGAGE; UNDERSTANDING HOW IMPOUND ACCOUNTS WORK 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By DIAN HYMER, SPECIAL TO THE TIMES; Distributed by Inman News Features. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 What is an impound account? 
</P>
<P>
 An impound account is an account that's set up by a lender to collect funds 
from the borrower that are used to pay future property tax bills and hazard 
insurance premiums. 
</P>
<P>
 After closing, you'll pay one-twelfth of your insurance premium and property 
tax bill to the lender each month for as long as you have an impound account. 
The impound amount is usually added to your principal and interest payment so 
that you make just one payment per month to the lender. The lender is then 
responsible for paying your property tax and insurance bills. 
</P>
<P>
 An impound account is almost always required if the borrower makes a down 
payment of 10% of the purchase price or less. Lenders, however, do have the 
option of requiring an impound account if the borrower makes a down payment of 
less than 20% of the purchase price. This requirement will vary from one lender 
to the next. 
</P>
<P>
 Money is collected from the borrower at closing to set up the impound account. 
The Real Estate Settlement Procedures Act (RESPA) limits how much a lender can 
require a buyer to deposit in an impound account. This amount will vary 
depending on when you close. If the property tax bill was recently paid and the 
next installment isn't due for some time, the amount required to start the 
impound account will be less than it'll be if the property taxes need to be 
paid in the near future. 
</P>
<P>
 The amount collected at closing will usually be enough to cover several months 
worth of taxes and insurance. Since the lender also collects the first year's 
hazard insurance premium at closing, an impound account requirement can add 
significantly to your closing costs. 
</P>
<P>
 Although most borrowers prefer not to have an impound account unless it's 
required, some borrowers prefer having one because it relieves them of the 
obligation of having to make several relatively large payments a year. An 
impound account might be a good idea if you're on a tight budget, or if you've 
had difficulty managing your money in the past. Even if an impound account 
isn't required, the lender gives you the option at closing of having one if you 
want. 
</P>
<P>
 First-Time Tip: The irony of the impound-account requirement is that it's 
required of borrowers who have the least amount of money to put down. Most 
cash-strapped first-time buyers have difficulty scraping together enough money 
for a 10% down payment, plus closing costs. This is precisely the situation 
where lenders insist on an impound account, which adds to the amount of cash 
the buyer will need at closing. 
</P>
<P>
 There is a way to get around this requirement. Many lenders will waive the 
impound account requirement if the borrower puts slightly more than 10% down. 
For example, if you can put enough cash down to equal 10.1% of the purchase 
price, you can probably avoid having an impound account. You'll still be 
required to buy private mortgage insurance (PMI) which protects the lender from 
a buyer default. PMI is required by most lenders when the borrower puts less 
than 20% cash down. 
</P>
<P>
 The Closing: If you do end up with an impound account, make sure to carefully 
monitor the payment of your property taxes and insurance premiums. Lenders make 
mistakes. If the lender fails to pay your property taxes or insurance bills 
when they're due, you could end up with a negative credit rating. The lender is 
responsible for making these payments, so you can justifiably argue the point 
with the credit rating agency. But it's usually a hassle to correct errors on 
credit reports. 
</P>
<P>
 For a copy of Dian Hymer's brochure, "Understanding the Purchase Contract , " 
please send $4 along with a self-addressed stamped envelop to Inman News 
Features -- Contract, 5335 College Ave., Suite 25, Oakland, Calif. 94618.  
</P>
</TEXT>
