<HEADLINE>
<P>
IN DEFENSE OF CHLORINE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Joan Bolton 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 In the midst of discussing alternatives to chlorine, it's important to note 
that the people who make and sell conventional chlorine products say that 
chlorine too often gets a bum rap. They say poor overall pool care is more to 
blame. 
</P>
<P>
 "The No. 1 factor is the pH. Too much acid or too much alkalinity will cause a 
lot of performance problems " said Jeff Cornett, president of Chem Lab 
Products, which produces and packages swimming pool chemicals. "Itchy, 
irritated skin, burning of the eyes, scale buildup on tile, on equipment -- 
those are generally associated with pH, not the performance of chlorine." 
</P>
<P>
 "Green hair is another issue," said Brian McDermott, president and CEO of 
Leslie's Swimming Pool Supplies, a chain that sells traditional chlorine 
products as well as alternative sanitizers. "Generally, the biggest culprit is 
copper, from copper algaecide. Or from a chemical imbalance, causing metals 
from the equipment to leach into the water." 
</P>
<P>
 McDermott added, "We really advise swimming pool owners to look at their care 
of the total system. It is rarely just one little thing that makes a dramatic 
difference." Joan Bolton 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Sidebar 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA092594-0167 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 082526 </DOCID>
<SOURCE>
<P>
 Los Angeles Times 
</P>
</SOURCE>
<DATE>
<P>
September 25, 1994, Sunday, Home Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
