<HEADLINE>
<P>
HOW SAFE IS CHLORINATED WATER? 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JOAN BOLTON, SPECIAL TO THE TIMES 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Is chlorinated water safe? 
</P>
<P>
 It depends on whom you talk to. 
</P>
<P>
 On the one hand, chlorine's nationwide use as a disinfectant in municipal 
water sources has prevented thousands of deaths from people drinking 
contaminated water. 
</P>
<P>
 Yet a landmark study in 1992 by Robert D. Morris of the Medical College of 
Wisconsin in Milwaukee concluded that people who drink chlorinated water run 
greater risks of contracting bladder and rectal cancer than those who drink 
non-chlorinated water. 
</P>
<P>
 Morris linked 4,200 new cases of bladder cancer and 6,500 new cases of rectal 
cancer in the United States each year to drinking chlorinated water. 
</P>
<P>
 A follow-up study by scientists at the National Institute of Environmental 
Health Sciences in 1993 pointed to byproducts formed when the chlorine reacted 
with contaminants as the likely causes of the cancers. 
</P>
<P>
 It's worth noting that the chlorine levels in our drinking water and our 
public swimming pools generally match: both are typically required to contain 
at least 1.5 parts per million free chlorine residual. (State code allows a 1 
ppm chlorine residual in public swimming pools if a stabilizing chemical is not 
used. However, Los Angeles County Department of Health Services official 
Richard Kebabjian estimates that at least 75% of public pools do use 
stabilizers. 
</P>
<P>
 But while scientists have studied the risks of chlorinating drinking water, 
they have paid scant attention to chlorine in swimming pools. 
</P>
<P>
 Among few studies is one that Kebabjian, as chief environmental health 
specialist for the county's recreational health program, is currently helping 
to conduct into the feasibility of drinking swimming pool water during an 
emergency, such as a major earthquake. Kebabjian expects to issue a report 
later this year. 
</P>
<P>
 Dr. Ken Cantor, an epidemiologist with the National Cancer Institute who 
specializes in analyzing the effects of chlorine in drinking water, knew of 
only two recent studies related to pool water. Scientists in Italy in 1990 and 
1993 monitored the chloroform levels of people swimming in indoor pools 
(chloroform is a common byproduct when chlorine reacts to organic substances in 
the water). 
</P>
<P>
 The Italian scientists found that all of the swimmers ingested at least some 
chloroform, but did not say whether that ingestion might affect the swimmers' 
health. 
</P>
<P>
 Absent much scientific inquiry into pool water, Morris said he is most 
concerned about breathing chlorine byproducts. 
</P>
<P>
 "You can absorb some of the chlorination byproducts in your skin. You can also 
absorb by inhaling," he said. "In swimming pools, you're dealing with prolonged 
exposure for people who are swimming regularly." 
</P>
<P>
 On a broader scale, last February the International Joint Commission on the 
Great Lakes region recommended phasing out all chlorine products. 
</P>
<P>
 And Environmental Protection Agency Administrator Carol Browner has proposed a 
new study into chlorine's health effects. A "national strategy for 
substituting, reducing, or prohibiting the use of chlorine and chlorinated 
compounds" would follow within three years. 
</P>
<P>
 "No decisions have been made," said EPA spokesman John Kasper. "Everything is 
contingent on the study, which has yet to be done." 
</P>
<P>
 Added Kasper: "There have been studies that have suggested that some of the 
byproducts are carcinogens . . . . (But) there was a time in this country when 
waterborne diseases ran rampant. Chlorine disinfection has huge, huge, health 
benefits that shouldn't be lost when you're talking about some of the other 
problems." 
</P>
</TEXT>
