<HEADLINE>
<P>
DEALS / ALLAN SLOAN: FITZGERALD WOULD HAVE APPRECIATED PERELMAN AND HIS PENDING 
PURCHASE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By ALLAN SLOAN, ALLAN SLOAN is a financial columnist for Newsday in New York. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 When F. Scott Fitzgerald wrote, "There are no second acts in American lives," 
he hadn't run into Ronald Perelman. Perelman -- the billionaire who controls 
Revlon cosmetics, Marvel comics and a flock of TV stations, among other things 
-- is trying to prove Fitzgerald wrong by performing a second act in the 
savings & loan business. 
</P>
<P>
 The first was a boffo success, at least for Perelman. By my count, Perelman 
made more than $1.2 billion buying failed S&Ls from the federal government in 
1988 and selling almost all his holdings last year. Now, Perelman is about to 
open Act II by buying most of a big troubled S&L, San Francisco-based First 
Nationwide, from Ford Motor Co. The show makes its debut Thursday, when the 
deal is supposed to be completed. 
</P>
<P>
 Will Act II equal Act I? Unlike the deal with the government, in which there 
was no way Perelman could not make a fortune, his deal with Ford carries 
serious risks. What's more, unlike his federal deal -- in which he had a naive 
seller and no meaningful competitors -- this time Perelman was dealing with a 
sophisticated seller and had to bid against two rivals: Golden West and Great 
Western, two of the best-regarded S&L companies in the country. 
</P>
<P>
 Taking a quick look at First Nationwide, it looks as if someone should have 
told Perelman to quit the S&L game while he was ahead. Although First 
Nationwide has $9.7 billion of deposits and operates in desirable markets such 
as California, Cleveland, New York City, Detroit, Miami and Chicago, it's 
plagued by high operating costs and riddled with bad loans. It's been a 
financial lemon for Ford since 1990.  
</P>
<P>
 The April deal called for Perelman to pay about $1.1 billion for First 
Nationwide, whose reported profits were barely enough to cover the interest 
cost on $1.1 billion. (Perelman, like all good billionaires, uses borrowed 
money to make acquisitions.) 
</P>
<P>
 But if you read the little-known documents that Perelman has filed in 
connection with his capital-raising for this deal, you find that he's working 
from a completely different script. Perelman, it turns out, is paying Ford only 
about $630 million in cash. So how is this a $1.1-billion deal? Because Ford 
will keep First Nationwide assets -- about two-thirds of which are troubled 
loans -- that it values at $444 million.  
</P>
<P>
 In addition, Ford is giving Perelman $50 million to cover severance payments 
for First Nationwide employees. The fewer he fires, the more money he keeps. 
</P>
<P>
 So for Perelman, the purchase price isn't exactly what it seemed to be. 
</P>
<P>
 In addition, First Nationwide, although no prize, is now in better shape than 
its public financial statements suggest. That's because those statements don't 
include the benefit of unloading the $444 million in assets onto Ford or the 
full benefit of recent deals in which Ford gave First Nationwide $1 billion in 
cash in return for $1 billion in bad loans. 
</P>
<P>
 Adjust for those items and for Perelman's planned sale of First Nationwide's 
Chicago deposits, as Perelman's filings do, and you've got an institution 
that's earning about $180 million before income taxes. 
</P>
<P>
 Crunch the numbers and you find that Perelman's annual cost of borrowing $685 
million to pay Ford and cover expenses will be a tad under $75 million. And his 
empire pays virtually no federal income tax, thanks to the $3.5 billion in tax 
benefits he has left over from Act I of our drama.  
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 So on paper, Perelman is about $100 million a year ahead. How can a deal like 
that be risky? 
</P>
<P>
 In two words: Lousy loans. 
</P>
<P>
 After the acquisition is completed, Perelman has the right to make Ford buy 
another $500 million in bad loans from First Nationwide. Many people think 
First Nationwide has lots more bad loans than that. 
</P>
<P>
 Which brings us to our second Ford: Gerald, no relation to the Ford Motor 
family or the former U.S. President, who runs Perelman's S&L show. Ford, an S&L 
expert, and Perelman, a deal-making expert, each probably accounted for about 
half of the $1.2 billion Perelman made in Act I. (I don't know how much Ford 
made.) Think of them as financial X-Men, super-heroes who use their mutant 
powers to make money. 
</P>
<P>
 Ford says he could safely outbid Perelman's rivals because his troops spent 
2,700 person-days examining suspect loans and will keep them, whereas the 
rivals planned to have Wall Street package them for a quick profit. "We could 
bid as a holder to term, not to purchase and resell those loans tomorrow 
afternoon at 2 o'clock," Ford said.  
</P>
<P>
 We'll see. That said, Perelman already has made a deal to sell First 
Nationwide's $1.3 billion of Chicago deposits to another bank for a whopping 
$94 million; he says in his filings that he also may sell the other $6 billion 
of non-California deposits. 
</P>
<P>
 You can see the plot unfolding: Perelman sells non-California deposits at 
premium prices, sheltering the profits with the tax benefits from Act I. While 
selling those deposits dear, our hero will buy California deposits at current, 
depressed prices. He thus builds First Nationwide's California operation into 
an efficient, mighty power and brings down the house by selling at a huge 
profit.  
</P>
<P>
 "This ain't church," Gerald Ford said. "We're really in it for the money." 
</P>
<P>
 Indeed. This part, Fitzgerald would have understood perfectly. "Let me tell 
you about the very rich," he wrote. "They are different from you and me."  
</P>
<P>
 Hmm. Maybe F. Scott really did have Ron Perelman in mind after all. 
</P>
</TEXT>
