<HEADLINE>
<P>
LAWMAKERS MUST SHIELD STATE'S DEFENSE JOBS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 * The Times is a welcome advocate for retaining California's military flight 
testing capability at Edwards Air Force Base. The real story is the continuing 
problem of California's legislative delegation NOT acting as a voting block to 
create new jobs. 
</P>
<P>
 Contrary to election-year rhetoric, California remains vulnerable to the 
integrated and united lobbying efforts of other states and special interest 
groups that are robbing California leaders and business of urgently needed 
assistance. Political and ideological egos must take a back seat to stop our 
manufacturing hemorrhage. If we want to save Edwards, we need to save military 
programs; if we want to convert defense manufacturing jobs to commercial 
applications, we have to save military programs long enough to convert; if we 
are committed to a market-driven, world-class manufacturing environment, we 
need creative job-creating legislation. 
</P>
<P>
 The time has come for our legislators and media organizations to take off 
their white gloves and fight to save this critical economic force. The issue at 
Edwards Air Force Base just reinforces the fact that service jobs depend on 
manufacturing jobs. Forget putting their heads together, circle the damn wagons 
and protect our defense and manufacturing jobs. 
</P>
<P>
 DAVID GOODREAU 
</P>
<P>
 Glendale 
</P>
